  "prompt": "If Buddhism is not a religion, then what is it?",
  "response": "The classification of Buddhism can be a subject of debate, and it often depends on how one defines \"religion.\" While many people consider Buddhism a religion, others argue that it is more of a philosophy or a way of life. Here are some perspectives on how Buddhism can be viewed:\n\n1. **Religion**: For many practitioners, Buddhism functions as a religion because it involves rituals, ethical guidelines, philosophical teachings, and in some traditions, devotional practices. It also addresses metaphysical questions and offers a path to spiritual enlightenment.\n\n2. **Philosophy**: Some view Buddhism as a philosophy because it provides a comprehensive framework for understanding the nature of reality, human suffering, and ethical living. It emphasizes personal experience, critical inquiry, and mindfulness.\n\n3. **Way of Life**: Buddhism can also be seen as a way of life that focuses on personal development and the pursuit of wisdom, compassion, and inner peace. This perspective emphasizes practical applications of Buddhist teachings in daily life.\n\n4. **Psychology**: With its emphasis on understanding the mind and its proclivities, some see Buddhism as a form of ancient psychology. Practices like meditation are seen as tools for mental and emotional well-being.\n\nThe diversity within Buddhism, spanning various cultures and interpretations, allows it to be many things to different people. Whether it is considered a religion, philosophy, way of life, or something else often depends on individual perspectives and contexts.",
